      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a pallet conveyor?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A pallet conveyor is a heavy-duty material handling system designed to transport loaded or empty pallets through packaging, warehousing, and manufacturing operations. Pallet conveyors use chain-driven live rollers (CDLR), heavy-duty powered rollers, drag chains, or slat-top chains to move loads typically weighing 500 to 4,000+ pounds. They connect palletizers, stretch wrappers, pallet labelers, staging areas, and shipping docks."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much weight can a pallet conveyor handle?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Standard pallet conveyors handle loads from 500 to 4,000 lbs. Light-duty pallet conveyors carry empty pallets and light loads up to 1,000 lbs. Medium-duty conveyors handle standard GMA pallets loaded to 2,000-2,500 lbs. Heavy-duty configurations support loads up to 4,000 lbs or more for applications like full drum pallets, heavy building materials, and automotive components. Load capacity depends on roller diameter, chain size, bearing rating, and frame construction."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between CDLR and drag chain pallet conveyors?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "CDLR (Chain-Driven Live Roller) conveyors use sprocket-driven steel rollers to carry pallets. The rollers are connected by a chain loop driven by one motor. CDLR works well for straight runs and supports accumulation by allowing rollers to slip under the chain. Drag chain conveyors use two or more strands of chain running in tracks to carry pallets directly on the chain surface. Drag chain conveyors handle heavier loads, work better for non-standard pallet sizes, and are simpler in construction, but they do not support accumulation without separate zones."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What pallet conveyor speed is typical for packaging lines?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Pallet conveyors in packaging lines typically run at 20-60 FPM (feet per minute). Palletizer discharge conveyors run at 20-40 FPM to match the palletizer cycle time. Transfer and staging conveyors run at 30-60 FPM. Stretch wrapper infeed conveyors match the wrapper cycle time, typically running only during pallet loading. Higher speeds (up to 80-100 FPM) are possible but rarely needed for pallet handling in packaging lines."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do pallet conveyors integrate with stretch wrappers?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Pallet conveyors feed loaded pallets into stretch wrappers and transport wrapped pallets to labeling or staging. The conveyor upstream of the wrapper stages one or two pallets in queue. A photo-eye signals the wrapper to accept the next pallet. The conveyor advances the pallet onto the wrapper turntable or into the wrapper ring. After wrapping, the downstream conveyor pulls the wrapped pallet out. Turntable stretch wrappers use conveyor-integrated turntables. Rotary arm wrappers keep the pallet stationary on the conveyor while the arm orbits."
      }
    }
  ]
