<BaseLayout title="Pallet Conveyor Systems: CDLR, Chain, Roller Types &#x26; Load Capacity | PackagingConveyor.com" description="Complete guide to pallet conveyor systems. Covers chain-driven live roller (CDLR), drag chain, roller, and turntable types. Load capacities from 500 to 4,000+ lbs, stretch wrap integration, and manufacturer comparison for Hytrol, Intelligrated, Dematic, TGW, and Bastian Solutions." canonical="https://packagingconveyor.com/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" schema={[breadcrumbSchema, faqSchema, articleSchema]}>

  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <nav class="bg-surface-dim border-b border-border" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-3">
      <ol class="flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-ink-muted">
        <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Home</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li><a href="/industries/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Industries</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li><a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Packaging Lines</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li class="text-ink font-semibold">Pallet Conveyors</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- Hero / AIO -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Packaging Line Conveyors</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-6">
        Pallet Conveyor Systems
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl space-y-4">
        <p>
          Pallet conveyors are heavy-duty conveyor systems that transport loaded and empty pallets through packaging, warehousing, and manufacturing operations. They use chain-driven live rollers (CDLR), drag chains, or heavy-duty powered rollers to move loads from 500 to 4,000+ pounds between palletizers, stretch wrappers, pallet labelers, staging areas, and shipping docks.
        </p>
        <p>
          Pallet conveyors form the backbone of every end-of-line packaging system. They connect the palletizer output to the stretch wrapper, then route wrapped pallets to staging lanes or directly to truck loading positions.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article>
  <!-- Pallet Conveyor Types -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="types-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Conveyor Types</div>
      <h2 id="types-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Pallet Conveyor Types: CDLR, Drag Chain, Roller &#x26; Turntable
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Chain-Driven Live Roller (CDLR)</h3>
        <p>
          <a href="/conveyor-types/cdlr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">CDLR conveyors</a> are the most common pallet conveyor type. Steel rollers mount in a heavy-gauge steel frame and connect through sprocket-and-chain drives powered by a single motor. The chain loop drives the rollers, which carry the pallet on their surface.
        </p>
        <p>
          CDLR advantages include roller slip capability (the chain can continue driving while rollers stop under a stationary pallet, enabling accumulation), wide load capacity range (1,000-4,000 lbs standard), and compatibility with standard GMA pallets. Hytrol's Model 26-CRRC and Intelligrated's (Honeywell) pallet conveyor lines use CDLR construction as their standard platform. <!-- VERIFY: Current Hytrol CDLR model numbers -->
        </p>
        <p>
          Roller diameter determines load capacity and durability. Common sizes:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
          <li><strong class="text-ink">2.5-inch diameter rollers:</strong> light-duty pallet conveyors, empty pallet handling, loads up to 1,500 lbs</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">3.5-inch diameter rollers:</strong> standard GMA pallet loads, 1,500-3,000 lbs, most common size</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">5-inch diameter rollers:</strong> heavy-duty applications, 3,000-4,000+ lbs, drum handling, steel/building materials</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-10 mb-4">Drag Chain Conveyors</h3>
        <p>
          <a href="/conveyor-types/chain-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Drag chain</a> pallet conveyors use two or three strands of heavy-duty chain running in steel or UHMW tracks. Pallets ride directly on the chain strands. The chain is driven by sprockets at one end and idles on sprockets at the other end.
        </p>
        <p>
          Drag chain suits non-standard pallet sizes, slave pallets, and applications where pallets are too damaged or irregular for reliable roller transport. Drag chain also handles heavier loads than CDLR because the load distributes across the full chain length rather than individual roller bearings. The disadvantage: drag chain does not support accumulation without separate zones, each with its own chain drive.
        </p>
        <p>
          Dematic and TGW use drag chain conveyors for pallet handling in high-throughput warehouse and distribution systems where pallets transfer between AS/RS (Automated Storage and Retrieval Systems) and outbound staging.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-10 mb-4">Heavy-Duty Powered Roller</h3>
        <p>
          Heavy-duty powered roller conveyors use belt-driven or line-shaft-driven large-diameter rollers. They serve applications requiring higher speeds than CDLR or where chain maintenance is undesirable. Belt-driven roller conveyors generate less noise than chain-driven systems and require less lubrication.
        </p>
        <p>
          <a href="/conveyor-types/live-roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Live roller conveyors</a> in heavy-duty configurations handle pallet loads using V-belt or round-belt drives between rollers. Load capacity depends on roller diameter, bearing rating, and belt tension.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-10 mb-4">Turntable Conveyors</h3>
        <p>
          Pallet turntables rotate pallets 90 or 180 degrees for direction changes in conveyor layouts. The turntable platform contains a short section of roller or chain conveyor that aligns with the incoming and outgoing conveyor lines. A motor or pneumatic actuator rotates the platform to the target angle.
        </p>
        <p>
          Turntables handle direction changes where right-angle <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">transfer conveyors</a> cannot accommodate the pallet size or weight. Turntable cycle times range from 5-15 seconds per rotation, which limits throughput compared to continuous-motion right-angle transfers. Hytrol and Bastian Solutions manufacture standard pallet turntable units.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-10 mb-4">Right-Angle Transfer (Chain Transfer)</h3>
        <p>
          Chain transfer conveyors move pallets at 90-degree angles without rotation. Pop-up chain strands rise between the rollers of a CDLR conveyor, lift the pallet off the rollers, and carry it perpendicular to the original direction. Chain transfers handle higher throughput than turntables because they operate continuously without a rotation cycle.
        </p>
        <p>
          Right-angle transfers serve as routing points in pallet conveyor systems, directing pallets to different staging lanes, dock doors, or storage rows based on PLC logic.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Load Capacity -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="load-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Load Capacity</div>
      <h2 id="load-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Pallet Conveyor Load Capacity and Sizing
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p>
          Pallet conveyor load capacity depends on roller diameter, roller spacing (pitch), bearing rating, chain size, and frame construction. Every component in the conveyor must carry the maximum expected load with a safety margin. Under-specifying any single component creates a weak link that limits the entire system.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Standard Pallet Types and Weights</h3>
      </div>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto -mx-4 px-4 mt-4">
        <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse min-w-[700px]">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b-2 border-ink">
              <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Pallet Type</th>
              <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Dimensions</th>
              <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Typical Loaded Weight</th>
              <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4">Conveyor Class</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="text-base text-ink-muted">
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">GMA (Grocery)</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">48" x 40"</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">1,500-2,500 lbs</td>
              <td class="py-4">Standard duty</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Euro Pallet</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">47.2" x 31.5"</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">1,000-2,000 lbs</td>
              <td class="py-4">Standard duty</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Beverage (heavy)</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">48" x 40"</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">2,500-3,500 lbs</td>
              <td class="py-4">Heavy duty</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Drum Pallet</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">48" x 48"</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">3,000-4,000+ lbs</td>
              <td class="py-4">Heavy duty</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Empty Pallets (stack)</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">48" x 40"</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">200-500 lbs</td>
              <td class="py-4">Light duty</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4 mt-8">
        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-4 mb-4">Conveyor Capacity Classes</h3>
        <p>
          Manufacturers categorize pallet conveyors into capacity classes based on maximum load rating:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Light duty (up to 1,500 lbs):</strong> Empty pallet handling, light consumer goods. Uses 2.5" diameter rollers on 6" pitch. Painted carbon steel frames.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Standard duty (1,500-3,000 lbs):</strong> GMA pallets loaded with cases and cartons. Uses 3.5" diameter rollers on 4-6" pitch. Standard for food, beverage, and consumer goods packaging lines. Hytrol, Intelligrated, and Bastian Solutions all offer standard-duty CDLR platforms.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Heavy duty (3,000-4,000+ lbs):</strong> Full beverage pallets, drums, building materials. Uses 5" diameter rollers on 3-4" pitch with heavy-gauge frames. Oversized bearings and #60 or #80 chain. Dematic and TGW build heavy-duty platforms for warehouse AS/RS integration.</li>
        </ul>
        <!-- VERIFY: Typical roller pitch specifications by capacity class across manufacturers -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Sizing Considerations</h3>
        <p>
          Conveyor width must accommodate the pallet width plus clearance on each side. Standard clearance is 2-4 inches per side. For a 40-inch-wide GMA pallet, the conveyor frame width is typically 46-48 inches (between rails). <!-- VERIFY: Standard frame width for GMA pallet conveyors -->
        </p>
        <p>
          Conveyor length per section depends on pallet length plus spacing. A typical staging zone holds one pallet per position plus 6-12 inches of gap for sensor spacing and pallet separation.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Stretch Wrap Integration -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="wrap-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">End-of-Line Integration</div>
      <h2 id="wrap-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Stretch Wrapper and Palletizer Integration
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p>
          Pallet conveyors integrate with palletizers and stretch wrappers at both ends of the end-of-line system. The conveyor design at each integration point must match the machine's cycle time, pallet orientation requirements, and elevation.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Palletizer Discharge</h3>
        <p>
          The conveyor at the palletizer discharge receives completed pallets and moves them toward the stretch wrapper. This conveyor must start and stop quickly to clear the palletizer output position before the next pallet pattern is complete. Standard palletizer discharge conveyors use CDLR or drag chain in a heavy-duty configuration.
        </p>
        <p>
          The conveyor should include 2-3 pallet positions of staging between the palletizer and the stretch wrapper. This buffer prevents the palletizer from stopping if the stretch wrapper is mid-cycle when the next pallet is ready. Photo-eye sensors at each position signal pallet presence to the PLC.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Stretch Wrapper Infeed and Outfeed</h3>
        <p>
          Two stretch wrapper types require different conveyor integration approaches:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Turntable stretch wrappers:</strong> The pallet transfers from the conveyor onto a rotating turntable. The turntable spins the pallet while a film carriage applies stretch film. After wrapping, the pallet transfers back onto the outfeed conveyor. The infeed and outfeed conveyors align with the turntable and use chain transfers or pop-up chain to move pallets on and off the turntable.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Rotary arm (straddle) stretch wrappers:</strong> The pallet remains stationary on the conveyor while a rotating arm orbits the pallet, applying film. No turntable transfer is needed. The pallet stays on the conveyor throughout the wrapping cycle. This simplifies conveyor integration and eliminates the turntable transfer cycle time.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-10 mb-4">Post-Wrap Handling</h3>
        <p>
          After stretch wrapping, pallets typically pass through a pallet labeler (which applies shipping labels to one or more faces), then route to staging lanes or directly to shipping dock positions. <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Transfer conveyors</a> and turntables route pallets to the correct lane based on order, destination, or truck assignment. The PLC reads barcode or RFID data to determine routing.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Accumulation -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="accum-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Accumulation</div>
      <h2 id="accum-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Pallet Accumulation and Staging
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p>
          Pallet <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation conveyors</a> queue loaded pallets between processes. CDLR conveyors support accumulation because the rollers can stop under a stationary pallet while the chain continues to drive. The chain slips on the roller sprocket, allowing pallets to accumulate without back-driving upstream pallets.
        </p>
        <p>
          Pallet accumulation conveyors divide into zones, each controlled by a photo-eye sensor. Each zone holds one pallet. The PLC releases pallets one zone at a time as downstream positions clear. This prevents pallet-to-pallet contact and allows orderly sequencing.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Staging Lane Configuration</h3>
        <p>
          High-throughput packaging operations use multiple parallel staging lanes fed by transfer conveyors. Each lane holds 3-10 pallets depending on available floor space and buffer time requirements. Pallets route to lanes by SKU, shipping destination, or truck assignment.
        </p>
        <p>
          Staging lane lengths depend on throughput and truck loading cycle time. A staging system sized correctly accumulates enough pallets to fill a truck (typically 20-26 pallets) without requiring the palletizer to stop. The formula:
        </p>
        <p class="font-mono text-ink bg-surface px-4 py-3 border border-border">
          <strong>Total Staging Positions = Pallets/hr x Truck Loading Time (hr) x Safety Factor (1.2-1.5)</strong>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Supplier Evaluation -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-ink-light" aria-labelledby="mfg-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent-bright mb-4">Supplier Evaluation</div>
      <h2 id="mfg-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-white tracking-wide mb-8">
        How to Evaluate a <span class="text-accent-bright">Pallet Conveyor Supplier</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-white/60 leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-white mb-2">Match the Supplier to the Application</h3>
          <p>Some suppliers focus on standard catalog pallet conveyor modules, while others specialize in engineered-to-order systems with controls, robotics, and warehouse software integration. Decide early whether you need a hardware supplier, a system integrator, or a turnkey automation partner.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-white mb-2">Ask About Installed Base and Service Support</h3>
          <p>Pallet conveyors are heavy-duty assets that often stay in service for decades. Ask how many similar pallet systems the supplier has commissioned, what service territory they cover, how quickly they can support a breakdown, and which spare parts are standard versus proprietary.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-white mb-2">Review the Controls Boundary</h3>
          <p>The biggest project risk is often at the interface between mechanical conveyor, controls, and upstream or downstream equipment. Clarify who owns PLC logic, field devices, safety zoning, communication with palletizers or wrappers, and final commissioning responsibility.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-white mb-2">Compare on Total Lifecycle Fit</h3>
          <p>Do not compare suppliers on quote price alone. Compare load rating margin, chain and bearing access, spare parts availability, maintenance labor, future expansion flexibility, and whether the design uses standard components your maintenance team can realistically support.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-white/60 mt-8">PackagingConveyor.com is not affiliated with any supplier. See our <a href="/about/" class="text-accent-bright hover:text-white font-semibold">about page</a> for our editorial approach.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Spec Comparison Table -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="spec-heading">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Specifications</div>
      <h2 id="spec-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-10">
        Pallet Conveyor Type <span class="text-accent">Comparison</span>
      </h2>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto -mx-4 px-4">
        <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse min-w-[800px]">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b-2 border-ink">
              <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Feature</th>
              <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">CDLR</th>
              <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Drag Chain</th>
              <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Heavy Roller</th>
              <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4">Turntable</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="text-base text-ink-muted">
